<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph>
4. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:227008" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pyramica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pyramica kiranae Makhan" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kiranae">Pyramica kiranae Makhan</taxonomicName>
, 2007: 4, figs 7, 8. Holotype and paratype workers, SURINAME: Kasikasima, 27.iii.1996 (D. Makhan) [not in USPS]. New junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:146630" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pyramica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pyramica subedentata (Mayr)" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subedentata">Pyramica subedentata</taxonomicName>
(Mayr, 1887).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph>
Comment. There is a slight possibility that 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:227008" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pyramica" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pyramica kiranae Makhan" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kiranae">kiranae</taxonomicName>
may be a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:146644" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pyramica" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pyramica trieces (Brown)" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trieces">trieces</taxonomicName>
(Brown, 1960), rather than 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:146630" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pyramica" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pyramica subedentata (Mayr)" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subedentata">subedentata</taxonomicName>
. The last two are very closely related and the characters that differentiate them (alitrunk pilosity and sculpture of the first gastral sternite) are not discernible in the photographs and are not mentioned in the descriptions. However, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:146644" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pyramica" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pyramica trieces (Brown)" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trieces">trieces</taxonomicName>
is known only from Central America, whereas 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:146630" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pyramica" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pyramica subedentata (Mayr)" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subedentata">subedentata</taxonomicName>
, apart from being a more common species, is also widespread in northern South America, with records from Colombia, Venezuela, Trinidad, Suriname, French Guiana, Guyana, Brazil and Peru.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
